      <h1><span id="elementSym" style="height: 140px; width:80px; background-color:#1ABC9C; color:#ECF0F1; border-radius: 3px;">&nbsp; F <span style="position:absolute; font-size: 20px;">9</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; Fluorine <small>by Gautam Mittal</small></h1>
      <p class="lead">The Past of the Most Reactive Element</p>
      <hr>
  <div class="infoSection">
      <h4>History</h4>
      <img src="fluorspar.jpg" style="height: 400px;" class="img-rounded img-responsive"/>
      <p class="img-comment">Fluorpar, or calcium fluoride. The original fluorine compound that was discovered.</p>
      In the early 1500s, a German scientist named Georgius Agricola described a mineral called fluorspar. Flurospar comes from Latin (fluere) meaning "to flow". He claimed that adding it to molten metal made the metal much easier to work with. But the uses of fluorspar were not only limited to this. It was also used for glass etching (it became a great etching material when mixed with acid). Fluorspar is actually calcium fluoride, a compound of fluorine and calcium, which is commonly found in nature. Other compounds that were later discovered included hydrofluoric acid. The discovery of these intriguing compounds led many scientists to experiment, and many started trying to see if they could separate the elements in hydrofluoric acid to get fluroine in its elemental form. Fluorine was finally isolated in 1886, by the chemist Henri Moissan. It was first isolated through the electrolysis of potassium hyrdrogen fluorine and anhydrous hydrofluoric acid. Because of Moissan's work in solving the mystery of fluorine, he was later awarded the 1906 Nobel Prize in Chemistry. The past of fluorine can be broken up into several major events:<br /><br />
      <li>In <font color="#1ABC9C">TURQUOISE</font>: The first fluorspar discoveries are made in 1530 by Georgius Agricola (fluorine in elemental form is still undiscovered).</li>
      <li>In <font color="#F1C40F">YELLOW</font>: The first experiements on fluorspar start in the early 1800s (hyrdofluoric acid is discovered, but fluorine itself as not yet been discovered).</li>
      <li>In <font color="#E74C3C">RED</font>: 1809-1813. First theories of hydrofluoric acid containing an undiscovered element called fluorine are made. First attempts at isolating this new element are made.</li>
      <li>In <font color="#2ECC71">GREEN</font>: 1886 - 1906. Henri Moissan's work led to the first successful isolation of fluorine and his awarding of the Nobel Prize.</li>
      <li>In <font color="#3498DB">BLUE</font>: 1906 - Present. Fluorine experiementation continues and new compounds are discovered as well as new uses for the element.</li>
      <br />
      <div class="progress">
